The IMF needs more Lagarde.
Davos – Lagarde had said she is open to serving another five-year term as the head of the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
She should be retained.
The IMF has never had a better leadership team than hers, and the IMF's Board of Governors should give her the opportunity to complete the work she has started.
Lagarde took office in July 2011 and inherited an institution in crisis.
The global financial collapse of 2008 and its subsequent economic fallout undermined the credibility of multilateral lending institutions led by the West and the Washington Consensus of free-market economics.
Lagarde's leadership helped restore the IMF's reputation.
Many eyes turned to her personal qualities — as they should.
She is candid, strong, warm, and touching.
The officials from various countries who met with her (often in delicate settings) all remarked on her courage in speaking the difficult truths while also being a sensitive listener.
These are important traits for an institution's leader who must negotiate terms of an agreement rather than dominate everything.
Lagarde told Europeans that their banks needed to be restructured, otherwise firewalls had to be put in place to prevent financial contagion. The advice, though unwelcome, was heeded.
Similarly, she is advocating loudly for IMF support to be provided to some countries – such as Greece, Pakistan, Tunisia, and Ukraine – which is crucial for global stability.
There are countless other examples.
The IMF is not particularly known for innovation and is usually not characterized by fervor.
Lagarde is starting to change this.
In the process, she gave this institution, which often prescribes bitter medicine, a compassionate face.
For example, helping to manage the refugee crisis in the Middle East was not originally within the IMF’s mandate.
However, under her leadership, the IMF adjusted its plans to allow the Jordanian government to allocate more funds to assist refugees displaced by the conflicts in Syria and Iraq (over one million people are living in camps within Jordan).
Similarly, in 2014, when the Ebola crisis struck West Africa, Lagarde led the IMF to use its available resources to provide debt relief to affected countries, enabling them to improve the compensation of doctors and nurses – a first for the Fund to use its capital in this manner.
Moreover, Lagarde recognized the three biggest challenges of our world today and took action against them.
First, she strongly advocated for more women to join the workforce, setting herself as an exemplar of the value of women in leadership positions.
She urged leaders in varied countries, from Saudi Arabia to Japan, to stop wasting such enormous talent resources and thereby realize their economic potential.
Next, under her leadership, the IMF also addressed the broader issue of income inequality.
This is not just a basic issue of fairness.
The IMF's research emphasizes that there is a direct link between reducing income disparities and boosting economic growth.
The IMF is not the first institution to demonstrate this point, but its stature makes the issue more prominent and urgent.
Individual efforts by Lagarde to promote this have been key to increasing its urgency.
Third, Lagarde played an important role in helping the world understand the full impact of technological changes – some of which will have frighteningly destructive effects.
For example, automation will continue to enhance the efficiency and reduce the costs of manufacturing, but it also means that the number of jobs created by economic growth will be less than in the past.
The political, economic, and social consequences of this emerging reality are worth our recognizing and serious study.
Lagarde made the IMF the centerpiece of this work.
Critics might argue that it is time for developing countries' representatives to lead the IMF.
After all, Lagarde is the 11th consecutive European to hold this position, and Europe's privilege in having such a monopoly is increasingly difficult to justify in today's world.
Some might also argue that the austerity measures supported by the IMF in Greece have not been fully effective, which suggests that she has already become detached from ordinary people.
Others have pointed out that she faces allegations involving a financial scandal with France, which could divert her attention from her work at the IMF.
Following her predecessor Dominique Strauss-Kahn's scandalous downfall, critics argue that the IMF cannot afford another such distraction.
Let's analyze these objections one by one.
The IMF (and the World Bank) should welcome leaders from beyond Europe and the United States.
But the goal of ending this Western privilege is to base the selection of leaders on merit rather than political considerations.
Lagarde is the best candidate for the IMF directorship, and emerging forces such as the BRICS (Brazil, Russia, India, and China) have not jointly nominated an alternative.
It may have been one of the factors in favor of having an European head of the IMF last year when the IMF decided to include the renminbi in the basket of currencies determining the value of its special drawing rights.
Furthermore, Lagarde impressed upon both Republicans and Democrats in the US Congress with her politically astute flexibility, ultimately securing approval for IMF governance reforms. These reforms not only bolstered the IMF’s arsenal for combating financial crises but also more accurately reflected the evolving dynamics of the global economy.
For example, now the BRICS countries have become among the top ten shareholders of the IMF.
On the Greek issue, Lagarde was rather frank – and some would say inappropriate – with her personal style of comments last year.
But she is certainly not the one to blame for the economic pain inflicted on the Greeks; her tenure at the IMF充分地表明，在IMF的历史上，从未有哪位总裁像她那样领导该组织采取了如此多的措施，以缓解危机中人民的痛苦。请注意，后半句的“她的任期”在翻译过程中被调整为“her tenure”，并且为了使句子更流畅和自然，进行了适当的调整。
Finally, France's accusations against Lagarde were opposed by the French Prosecutor General, and Lagarde was at most only tangentially involved.
The world urgently needs a leader committed to making the world safer and more prosperous.
Lagarde has already proven herself to be such a leader, committed to adapting the IMF for the 21st century.
She deserves the opportunity to see it through to the end.
